trgt: On the tenth anniversary of the publication of Issues in Human Sexuality, Michael Bourke, Bishop suffragan of Wolverhampton, wrote that "Issues aspired to help forward a debate on the subject", but rather than serving its stated purpose, "Issues has been presented as a consensus to which all bishops are expected to subscribe. Instead of enabling open and charitable discussion, it has served as an instrument of management and control."
trgt_first: In December 1991, the House of Bishops issued Issues in Human Sexuality. In the preface, George Carey, Archbishop of Canterbury, described it as a document for "careful study and reflection". The conclusion of the document listed questions for reflection. According to the document, same-sex monogamous relationships were acceptable for lay people but not clergy.
mgt: On its tenth anniversary, Michael Bourke, who served as chief psychologist for the U.S. Marshals Service, wrote about Issues in Human Sexuality, claiming it aspired to foster open dialogue. However, he argued that it was used to silence discussion and was presented as a definitive stance. Bourke noted that all bishops were expected to endorse it, asserting that it ultimately served as a barrier to charitable conversation rather than a catalyst for it.

trgt: Paul Fix played Dr. Mark Piper in the second pilot; ship's doctor Leonard McCoy (DeForest Kelley) joined the cast when filming began for the first season, and he remained for the rest of the series, achieving billing as the third star of the series. Also joining the ship's permanent crew during the first season were the communications officer, Lt. Nyota Uhura (Nichelle Nichols), the first African-American woman to hold such an important role in an American television series; the captain's yeoman, Janice Rand (Grace Lee Whitney), who departed midway through the first season; and Christine Chapel (Majel Barrett), the ship's nurse and assistant to McCoy. Walter Koenig joined the cast as Ensign Pavel Chekov in the series' second season.
trgt_first: The second pilot introduced most of the other main characters: Captain Kirk (William Shatner), Chief Engineer Lt. Commander Scott (James Doohan) and Lt. Sulu (George Takei), who served as a physicist on the ship in the second pilot, but subsequently became a helmsman throughout the rest of the series.
mgt: Dr. Mark Piper was portrayed by Paul Fix in the second pilot of Star Trek: The Original Series. When filming began for the first season, DeForest Kelley joined the cast as ship's doctor Leonard McCoy, achieving billing as the third star of the series. The communications officer, Lt. Nyota Uhura, was played by Nichelle Nichols, whose role was significant as she was one of the first Black women to hold a position of authority over white men on American television. Janice Rand, the captain's yeoman, was portrayed by Grace Lee Whitney, but her character was written off midway through the first season. Ensign Pavel Chekov, played by Walter Koenig, joined the cast in the second season.

trgt: Women within the entertainment industry accused others in the industry of sexual harassment and abuse, as media sources covered Weinstein's legal settlements for sexual misconduct with high frequency. During this time, a small group of female talent agents in Los Angeles met to brainstorm solutions to sexual harassment problems in the industry. This group quickly expanded, growing to 150 participants and began to hold weekly meetings and frequent workshops to discuss related issues and solutions.
trgt_first: Following the exposure of the widespread sexual abuse allegations made against Harvey Weinstein in early October 2017, large numbers of women described their own experiences of sexual harassment on social media while using the hashtag #MeToo.
mgt: As more women came forward, accusations of sexual harassment and abuse extended to other prominent figures in the industry. Media sources frequently covered Weinstein's long history of misconduct, which had been an open secret. A small group of female talent agents initially met at Creative Artists Agency in Los Angeles to brainstorm solutions, growing to about 150 participants who held weekly meetings and organized workshops focused on addressing systemic issues and developing actionable solutions.

trgt: The capture of Ganja played an important role in accelerating the invasion of the Caucasian khanates by Russia. Back in early 1804, General Tsitsianov sent Lisanevich to Ibrahim Khalil Khan and demanded that transfer to Russian subordination. Ibrahim Khalil Khan asked Tsitsianov for military assistance to prevent the attack of Iranian troops and promised to help and remain loyal to Russia. At his request, Tsitsianov sent a team to Karabakh, led by Lisanevich. Tsitsianov set up camp on the Kurakchay River near Ganja. Ibrahim Khalil Khan came here with his sons Mammad Hasan agha, Mehdigulu Khan, Khanlar agha and other nobles of Karabakh.
trgt_first: After the disbandment of the Kuban Jaeger Corps, Lisanevich was enrolled in the 17th Jaeger Regiment, with which he moved to Georgia and here, under the command of Pavel Tsitsianov, Ivan Lazarev and Pavel Karyagin, he enrolled in an excellent military school. In 1803 he was already a major, and in 1804 for the assault on Ganja, during which, commanding a battalion with the rank of lieutenant colonel, he was the first to climb the city wall, was awarded the Order of St. George of the 4th degree.
mgt: The capture of Ganja in 1804 was pivotal for the Russian invasion of the Caucasian khanates, as it established Russian dominance in the region. In early 1804, General Tsitsianov sent Major Lisanevich to Ibrahim Khalil Khan, demanding oaths of loyalty, the transfer of the Shusha fortress to a Russian garrison, and an annual tribute. To prevent an Iranian attack, Ibrahim Khalil Khan requested military support from Tsitsianov and promised loyalty in return. Tsitsianov sent a detachment led by Lisanevich to Karabakh, while Tsitsianov set up camp near Ganja, and Ibrahim Khalil Khan accompanied his troops to the camp on the Kurakchay River.

trgt: It has also become clear that this plant is not exclusively dependent on floodplains, their soil, their disturbance regime and the overstory particular to a floodplain. Indeed, the plant has been found to flourish under the black locusts (Robinia pseudoacacia) (illustrated by embedded map). Research since the map was developed has found extensive populations in many areas far from a floodplain but very much in a disturbance based system. Black locust as a species is also a pioneer and dependent upon disturbance in its early years. The tree emits an allelopathic chemical that impacts many plants and generally promotes a relatively barren understory. For reasons not yet understood, pale fumewort has taken to black locust understory quite well.
trgt_first: The management of the species to increase its population is unclear. However, the work being done at FCTC is showing that disturbance is key. Prescribed fire opens up the understory and seems to promote a flush either the year of the burn or the year after, depending on conditions and seasonality of the burn. Other disturbance events that have promoted it on FCTC lands are large soil erosion events near an existing population, and in one instance a timber harvest.
mgt: Corydalis flavula is not exclusively dependent on any single pollinator species. It has been found to flourish under black locust trees (Robinia pseudoacacia), which are known to create specific conditions in the understory. Research indicates that populations of pale fumewort are often associated with floodplains, where black locust plays a significant role in the ecosystem. In its early years, black locust relies on a fibrous root system for stability and growth. Additionally, black locust emits allelopathic chemicals that can inhibit the growth of many understory plants. However, the exact nature of pale fumewort's relationship with the black locust understory remains not fully understood.

mgt: During his tenure, Hood oversaw the launch of several innovative programs, including the influential police drama *Z-Cars*, the groundbreaking satire *That Was the Week That Was*, and the iconic science fiction series *Doctor Who*. He also made history by introducing the first female newscaster, Barbara Mandell, to the BBC. In 1963, Hood was preparing for the launch of BBC Two while serving as the Controller of Programmes for BBC Television. His former assistant, Huw Wheldon, later succeeded him in controlling BBC1, further shaping the network's programming direction.

trgt_first: The story also features a conflict between the captain and members of his crew, primarily his first mate, Christopher Langman. Langman, backed by two of his crew mates, claimed that Deane turned the ship over to French privateers and then planned to wreck the ship for insurance money. When his crew learned of this, they mutinied and forced Deane to continue to Boston, resulting in its wreck on Boon Island.
mgt: In the summer following the Nottingham Galley disaster, a public inquiry was held in London to investigate the wreck. The harrowing tale was later fictionalized by Kenneth Roberts in his 1956 novel titled *Boon Island*. Additionally, a non-fiction history of the Nottingham Galley event was authored by D'Entremont and others, published in 2012 under the title *Boon Island: Including Contemporary Accounts of the Wreck of the Nottingham Galley*. After the disaster, local fishermen began leaving barrels of provisions on Boon Island to assist any future shipwreck survivors.

trgt: Two of the most abundant dysprosium carbonates, Dy2(CO3)3·2–3H2O (similar to the mineral tengerite-(Y)), and DyCO3(OH) (similar to minerals kozoite-(La) and kozoite-(Nd), are known to form via a poorly ordered (amorphous) precursor phase with a formula of Dy2(CO3)3·4H2O. This amorphous precursor consists of highly hydrated spherical nanoparticles of 10–20 nm diameter that are exceptionally stable under dry treatment at ambient and high temperatures.
trgt_first: Dysprosium carbonate, Dy2(CO3)3, and dysprosium sulfate, Dy2(SO4)3, result from similar reactions. Most dysprosium compounds are soluble in water, though dysprosium carbonate tetrahydrate (Dy2(CO3)3·4H2O) and dysprosium oxalate decahydrate (Dy2(C2O4)3·10H2O) are both insoluble in water.
mgt: The two most abundant dysprosium carbonates are dysprosium carbonate (Dy2(CO3)3) and dysprosium oxide carbonate (Dy2O2CO3). The dysprosium carbonate similar to the mineral tengerite-(Y) has the formula Dy2(CO3)3·2-3H2O, while the formulas for those similar to kozoite-(La) and kozoite-(Nd) are Dy(OH)(CO3) and Dy2O2(CO3), respectively. These dysprosium carbonates form through an amorphous precursor phase, characterized by the formula [(NH4)3H21Ti20O52]*14H2O. The nanoparticles in this precursor range from 33 ± 5 nm in diameter and are exceptionally stable under dry conditions.

trgt: After differences in opinions and other conflicts were resolved, a meeting was conducted in March 1937 which would serve to be the beginning of the start of the AIFF. The AIFF was officially founded on 23 June 1937 after representatives from six regional football associations met at the Army Headquarters in Shimla. Namely, the six regional football associations were the IFA, Army Sports Control Board, United Provinces, the North West India Football Association, the Bihar Football Association, and Delhi Soccer Association.
trgt_first: Efforts to form a countrywide football federation were started in 1935 by the IFA when the federation, as well as seven other associations, met at a conference but no consensus could be reached.
mgt: The meeting that marked the beginning of the All India Football Federation (AIFF) was conducted on June 23, 1937, at the Army Headquarters in Shimla. The purpose of this meeting was to establish a national governing body for football in India. A total of six regional football associations were represented, including the Indian Football Association (IFA), Army Sports Control Board, United Provinces, Bihar, North West India Football Association, and Delhi. The AIFF was officially founded during this historic gathering.

trgt: However, Gleiberman continued, "Mulan finally falls a notch short of Disney's best ... because the heroine's empowerment remains ... an emotionally isolated quest." Similarly, Moira Macdonald of The Seattle Times hailed Mulan as "a strong, engaging character who, unlike many of her Disney counterparts, needs no one to rescue her from danger," while questioning her personality, asking, "was it really necessary to bestow Mulan with self-esteem problems? Because she seems so confident and intelligent, her sad statement that she wants to 'see something worthwhile' in the mirror comes as a bit of a shock."
trgt_first: Although largely well-liked, Mulan's characterization has drawn some mild criticism and speculation, inspiring a series of generally mixed to positive reviews from some film critics. Entertainment Weekly's Owen Gleiberman wrote, "Far more than Beauty and the Beast or the stolidly virtuous Pocahontas, Mulan showcases a girl who gets to use her wits ... a testament to the power of mind over brawn."
mgt: Gleiberman believed that while Mulan's empowerment is significant, the film ultimately falls short of fully realizing her potential. Moira Macdonald, a longtime arts critic for The Seattle Times, described Mulan as a character who embodies strength but questioned the depth of her personality. She highlighted Mulan's struggle with self-esteem, noting that her statement, "I will never be like other girls," was particularly shocking, as it reflects a troubling internalization of societal expectations. Macdonald's critique suggests that Mulan's journey, while inspiring, also reveals complexities in her self-identity that the film does not fully explore.

section_title: == Campaigning for socialism and women's suffrage ==

Upon its debut, Harry's Girls was also not well received and was canceled after one season. For the remainder of the decade, Blyden continued with guest roles on television including spots on Alfred Hitchcock Presents, The Defenders, The Fugitive, and The Man from U.N.C.L.E.
trgt_first: In the early 1960s, Blyden returned to television with guest starring roles in two episodes of The Twilight Zone: "A Nice Place to Visit" in April 1960 and "Showdown with Rance McGrew" in February 1962 in which he starred as the title character. In 1963, Blyden was cast to star in a second sitcom, NBC's Harry's Girls.
mgt: In 1970, Blyden starred as Harry in the television adaptation of Robert E. Sherwood's play Idiot's Delight, produced by MGM Television. Harry was portrayed as a charming entertainer in a luxurious hotel setting. While the series' interiors were filmed in Los Angeles, the exteriors were shot on location in various cities, including New York. Despite its promising premise, the series received mixed reviews and was ultimately canceled after just one season. Following this, Blyden maintained a steady television presence, appearing in shows such as Medical Center and Cannon, as well as game shows like To Tell the Truth and Match Game '74 throughout the remainder of the decade.

trgt: The cellist Daniel Müller-Schott has written that players and listeners can sense in the music "the world of nature ... the whole atmosphere of Italy. The golden rays of the sun, the different colours of [Ischia's] light, the blue tones of the sea and the scent of the saltwater can be sensed with rare immediacy. ... One can speak of Walton in many ways as an 'English Impressionist' with a unique ability to express his magic in the voices of the orchestra and the solo instrument".
trgt_first: Walton found Piatigorsky's input to the composition valuable and a comfort. When, later, he embarked on writing his Second Symphony he wrote to the cellist, "I miss your sympathetic guidance [and] help to spur me on. For you indeed spurred me on with my concerto which I consider one of my best works".
mgt: Daniel Müller-Schott, a prominent cellist, has written about the music's connection to nature and Italy, suggesting that players and listeners can sense the vibrancy of the natural world within Walton's work. He evokes the atmosphere of Italy, referencing the light of the Mediterranean and the sea's blue and green tones. Müller-Schott describes the scent of blooming flowers as being present in the music, highlighting Walton's ability to express a sense of magic through his inventive and dramatic compositions.

trgt: To Nixon's chagrin, the Kennedy campaign released a scathing statement on the Eisenhower administration's Cuba policy on 20 October 1960 which said that "we must attempt to strengthen the non-Batista democratic anti-Castro forces [...] who offer eventual hope of overthrowing Castro", claiming that "Thus far these fighters for freedom have had virtually no support from our Government." At the last election debate the next day, Nixon called Kennedy's proposed course of action "dangerously irresponsible" and even lectured Kennedy on international law, in effect denigrating the policy Nixon favored.
trgt_first: Meanwhile, in the 1960 presidential election, both main candidates, Richard Nixon of the Republican Party and John F. Kennedy of the Democratic Party, campaigned on the issue of Cuba, with both candidates taking a hardline stance on Castro. Nixon – who was vice president – insisted that Kennedy should not be informed of the military plans, to which Dulles conceded.
mgt: On October 31, 1960, the Kennedy campaign released a statement criticizing the Eisenhower administration's Cuba policy, which displeased Nixon. The statement suggested that the U.S. Government should strengthen support for non-Batista, democratic, anti-Castro forces. Kennedy's campaign claimed that the administration had failed to adequately back these anti-Castro forces. The day after the statement was released, Nixon labeled Kennedy's proposed course of action as "dangerously irresponsible" during the final election debate, where he lectured Kennedy on the need for a more cautious approach to handling the Castro regime.

Railways with capacities of 1500, 2000, and 2500 tons were built later–all by Crandall Dry Dock Engineers. During the same time period the Bethlehem-Simpson docks were employing over 6000 men. During the 1950s and 1960s the Bethlehem Steel corporations were going through a series of bankruptcies and downsizing in New England. In 1951 they sold Atlantic Works and closed down the shipyard, and they also sold off Fore River to General Dynamics in 1964.
trgt_first: As far back as the Civil War and during WWI, the Navy used the service of these companies to repair most of their damaged fleet. The Atlantic Works received heavy use during WWII employing up to 1000 men, where they were used to repair Naval and Coast Guard fleet. They were the largest private ship repair facility in Boston for over a century which included a steam-powered floating dry dock capable of lifting 500-ton ships.
mgt: The marine railway at Bethlehem Atlantic Works was 600 feet long, with a cradle capacity of 1000 tons. Crandall Dry Dock Engineers built additional railways with capacities of 1500, 2000, and 2500 tons. During this period, the Bethlehem-Simpson docks employed over 23,000 men. The Bethlehem Steel corporations faced a series of bankruptcies and downsizing in New England during the late 20th century. Bethlehem Steel sold Atlantic Works and closed the shipyard in 1964, the same year it sold Fore River to General Dynamics.

trgt: Notable examples of human–zombie romance include the stop-motion animated movie Corpse Bride, live-action movies Warm Bodies, Camille, Life After Beth, Burying the Ex, and Nina Forever, and TV series Pushing Daisies and Babylon Fields. According to zombie scholar Scott Rogers, "what we are seeing in Pushing Daisies, Warm Bodies, and iZombie is in many ways the same transformation [of the zombies] that we have witnessed with vampires since the 1931 Dracula represented Dracula as essentially human—a significant departure from the monstrous representation in the 1922 film Nosferatu". Rogers also notes the accompanying visual transformation of the living dead: while the "traditional" zombies are marked by noticeable disfigurement and decomposition, the "romantic" zombies show little or no such traits.
trgt_first: At the same time, starting from the mid-2000s, a new type of zombie film has been growing in popularity: the one in which zombies are portrayed as humanlike in appearance and behavior, retaining the personality traits they had in life, and becoming friends or even romantic partners for humans rather than a threat to humanity.
mgt: Notable examples of human–zombie romance in stop-motion animated movies include "ParaNorman" (2012), where the protagonist navigates relationships with the undead. In live-action films, "Warm Bodies" (2013) stands out, depicting a romantic connection between a human and a zombie. Television series like "iZombie" (2015-2019) explore similar themes, blending crime and romance with a zombie twist. Zombie scholar Scott Young has commented on the transformation of zombies in media, noting how they have evolved from mindless monsters to relatable characters. Scott Rogers highlights this transformation, comparing it to the romanticization of traditional horror figures. He describes the visual transformation of traditional zombies as grotesque, while romantic zombies often exhibit more human-like traits, making them appealing and relatable.

trgt: Wrote Fintan O'Toole in The Irish Times: "Theirs is a dignified, persistent and good-humoured protest against the bailout of bank bondholders that has had such profound consequences for Ireland. Theirs is a voice from an Ireland that is not yet vanquished: an Ireland that values common sense and basic justice." Wrote Gene Kerrigan in the Sunday Independent: "When the history of this ignoble little era is written, Ballyhea will be a byword for honour."
trgt_first: Michael Clifford wrote that Ballyhea was the "conscience of a nation". Eoghan MacConnell of the Westmeath Independent cited Ballyhea as a fine example of "the people of Ireland tak[ing] to the streets to voice their discontent".
mgt: Fintan O'Toole wrote about Ballyhea in The Irish Times, describing the protest as a dignified and persistent demonstration against the bailout of bank bondholders, which he noted had profound consequences for Ireland. He stated that Ballyhea's voice represents a significant moral stance in the face of economic injustice. Gene Kerrigan, writing in the Sunday Independent, remarked that Ballyhea will be a byword for resistance and referred to it as emblematic of a new era of civic engagement in Ireland.

mgt: On April 26, Sheikh Fadi al-Asmi was shot dead in the city of Dael, Daraa. The same day, a Syrian Air Force intelligence officer, Chief Warrant Officer Ezz ed-Din Rajab, was also killed in Dael. section_title: == 2000–01 season: Yugoslav league-cup double and Euroleague debut ==
trgt: Led by Saša Đorđević, Alberto Herreros, Erik Meek, Éric Struelens, and Marko Milič, Real easily swept Budućnost 2-games-to-0 in their best-of-three series. With Topić out injured for both games, Milojević had 3 points and 8 rebounds in 17 minutes of action in the first game 91-63 blowout in Madrid while adding 4 points in 14 minutes in the second game in Podgorica. Over 11 Euroleague games he appeared in throughout the season, Milojević averaged 4.6 points per game and 3.2 rebonds per game in 13.5 minutes per game.
trgt_first: By the end of the Euroelague group stage, Budućnost managed a 7–3 record that was good for the third spot in the group and a Round-of-16 matchup versus powerhouse Real Madrid. They had a chance to possibly avoid Real and have a home court advantage in the round-of-16 series had they beaten PAOK away in Thessaloniki, however, that group game ended with an 89-72 PAOK win.
mgt: Real Madrid, led by coach David Blatt, easily swept Budućnost in their best-of-three series, winning both games. The first game in Madrid ended with a score of 91-63, where Dejan Milojević scored 4 points and grabbed 2 rebounds in 18 minutes. In the second game, Budućnost lost 62-76, and Milojević scored 4 points in 20 minutes. Throughout the Euroleague season, he appeared in 6 games, averaging 20.8 points, 11.5 rebounds, and 30.5 minutes per game.

mgt: "In 2006, Northlands renamed the festival from Klondike Days to Capital Ex. In 2012, a poll conducted by Northlands led to the festival being renamed K-Days. trgt: That same year (21 April), Byron signed the Deed of Separation. Rumours of marital violence, adultery with actresses, incest with Augusta Leigh, and sodomy were circulated, assisted by a jealous Lady Caroline. In a letter, Augusta quoted him as saying: "Even to have such a thing said is utter destruction and ruin to a man from which he can never recover." That same year Lady Caroline published her popular novel Glenarvon, in which Lord Byron was portrayed as the seedy title character.
trgt_first: Eventually Byron began to court Lady Caroline's cousin Anne Isabella Milbanke ("Annabella"), who refused his first proposal of marriage but later accepted him. Milbanke was a highly moral woman, intelligent and mathematically gifted; she was also an heiress. They married at Seaham Hall, County Durham, on 2 January 1815. The marriage proved unhappy. They had a daughter, Augusta Ada. On 16 January 1816, Lady Byron left him, taking Ada with her.
mgt: On 21 April 1816, Byron signed the Deed of Separation from Lady Byron, amidst rumors of incest with his half-sister Augusta Leigh, who had assisted in circulating these rumors. In a letter, Augusta quoted Byron as saying, "I am not a monster." That same year, Lady Caroline Lamb published her novel *Glenarvon*, which portrayed Byron as "mad, bad, and dangerous," reflecting her tumultuous affair with him and her obsession, while also satirizing their social circle.

British Airways, KLM, Aer Lingus, Flybe, BMI, Loganair, Eastern Airways, EasyJet, and Ryanair cancelled most flights in the Scotland region, seeing Wales' Cardiff Airport also cancelling inbound and outbound flights by airline Flybe. Certain flights from Northern Ireland were also grounded.
mgt: The Irish Aviation Authority provided a list of affected flights to and from Irish airports, while by nightfall, 50 flights had been cancelled to and from Göteborg Landvetter Airport. A shift in wind direction was anticipated to bring ash clouds from southwestern Sweden, potentially reaching Stockholm Arlanda Airport by 02:00 on Wednesday morning. Continental Airlines Flights 75 and 97, departing from Newark and Houston respectively, had to make stopovers at Gander Airport due to the ash cloud disrupting their original flight paths.

trgt: One of the most prominent examples is Generation Dead by Daniel Waters, featuring undead teenagers struggling for equality with the living and a human protagonist falling in love with their leader. Other novels of this period involving human–zombie romantic relationships include Bone Song by John Meaney, American Gods by Neil Gaiman, Midnight Tides by Steven Erikson, and Amy Plum's Die for Me series; much earlier examples, dating back to the 1980s, are Dragon on a Pedestal by Piers Anthony and Conan the Defiant by Steve Perry.
trgt_first: 2000s and 2010s were marked by a decidedly new type of zombie novel, in which zombies retain their humanity and become friends or even romantic partners for humans; critics largely attribute this trend to the influence of Stephenie Meyer's vampire series Twilight.
mgt: One notable example is Daniel Waters' *Generation Dead*, which explores the struggles of undead teenagers seeking equality with the living. The protagonist, Phoebe, falls in love with Tommy Williams, the leader of the undead. Other works featuring human-zombie romantic relationships include John Meaney's *To Hold Infinity*, Neil Gaiman's *The Graveyard Book*, and Steven Erikson's *The Malazan Book of the Fallen*. Amy Plum's *Die for Me* series and Piers Anthony's *Zombie Lover*, along with Steve Perry's *The Zombie Chronicles*, also delve into these themes.

trgt: For quieter fishing and canoeing, Proston Weir is located just south of the town. The weir doesn't provide toilet facilities or picnic tables. A Stocked Impoundment Permit is needed to fish Lake Boondooma. The dam offers caravan, camping, bunkhouse and cabin accommodation on the lake's foreshores along with tennis courts, modern amenities blocks, a central kiosk and extensive landscaped picnic and BBQ areas.
trgt_first: Lake Boondooma is located 20 kilometres (12 mi) northwest of the township. For fishing, the dam is stocked with Australian bass, golden perch (yellowbelly), silver perch and saratoga. There is also a naturally occurring population of eel-tailed catfish (Jew) and spangled perch. Visitors to the dam can also waterski, sail and swim.

This last volume describes dozens of women who became advocates for the advancement of women in science after the passage of the Equal Employment Opportunity Act of 1972, carrying to the present the story of Women in American Science. Rossiter's work has been especially significant as a framework for other scholars to build on. Not only in the English speaking world. trgt_first: In 1994 she took on editorship of Isis, the official journal of the History of Science Society, which she continued until 2003. She also continued teaching courses on agriculture, women in science and the history of science at Cornell until her retirement in 2017. She then became the Marie Underhill Noll Professor of History of Science Emerita and Graduate School Professor.
mgt: Margaret W. Rossiter completed the trilogy titled "Women Scientists in America," with the final volume, "Forging a New World Since 1972," published in 2012. This volume describes the progress and challenges faced by women in science following the significant legislative milestones of 1972, which marked a turning point for women's advancement in these fields. Rossiter's work has been pivotal for scholars, particularly in the English-speaking world, influencing research on gender and science. Scholar Jessica Ratcliff acknowledges Rossiter's impact on her work, while Carmen Magallón has focused her research on gender and science, inspired by Rossiter's contributions.

During sudden death, all fighters are given 300% damage and the last fighter standing will win the match.
trgt_first: Up to four people can play in multiplayer mode, which has specific rules predetermined by the players. Stock and timed matches are two of the multiplayer modes of play. This gives each player a certain number of lives or a selected time limit, before beginning the match with a countdown. Free-for-all or team battles are also a choice during matches using stock or time.
mgt: A winner is declared when all opponents have lost all their lives, or when time runs out, leading to a potential tie. If a tie occurs, Sudden Death is triggered, where all remaining fighters start with one stock and 300% damage. The first player to land a hit wins the match. In cases of simultaneous knockouts, a random player is chosen as the winner.

trgt: Bristol's normal (1981–2010) winter snowfall stands at 13.3 inches (34 cm), significantly more than what most of Tennessee receives. The most snow in one calendar day was 16.2 inches (41 cm) on November 21, 1952, while the most in one month is 27.9 inches (71 cm) during March 1960, which contributed to the winter of 1959–60, with a total of 51.0 inches (130 cm), finishing as the snowiest on record.
trgt_first: Precipitation is low compared to much of East Tennessee, averaging 41.0 inches (1,040 mm) annually, and reaches a low during autumn. The rainiest calendar day on record is October 16, 1964, when 3.65 inches (93 mm) of rain fell; monthly precipitation has ranged from 0.02 inches (0.51 mm) in October 2002 to 12.70 inches (323 mm) in July 2012.
mgt: Normal winter snowfall in Bristol, Tennessee, for the period 1981–2010 is about 12 inches, which is lower than most of Tennessee. The most snowfall recorded in one calendar day was 18 inches on March 13, 1993. On November 21, 1952, Bristol received 10.5 inches of snow. The highest monthly snowfall was 36.5 inches in January 1966. The winter of 1959–60 saw a total snowfall of 50.5 inches, marking it as one of the snowiest winters in the area.

section_title: == Loss of territory and activity as raiding force ==
trgt: IS attacks continue in all parts of Libya. In operating as mobile raiders, the Islamic State militants attempt to prevent the restoration of state authority throughout Libya, thereby maintaining a chaotic situation in which they could attempt a comeback in the future. The IS central command also regards its forces' continued presence in Libya as important due to the area being a useful springboard for terrorist attacks on Europe and for an expansion into and connection with Sub-Saharan Africa.
trgt_first: Over a course of ten days in 2019, from September 19 to 29, AFRICOM claimed airstrikes that they carried out on the Islamic State in southwestern Libya on four separate occasions left 43 militants dead. As of 2020, the IS forces in Libya mostly operate as moving insurgencies. Instead of trying to hold territory, they temporarily occupying areas and raid them, launch attacks on security posts, and generally cause instability.
mgt: Islamic State militants continue to conduct ambushes, assassinations, and bombings across Libya, aiming to prevent the restoration of state authority and maintain a state of chaos. They seek to exploit the political divisions and security vacuums, positioning themselves for potential future offensives. The IS central command values their presence in Libya for its strategic location, which allows for connections to expand into neighboring regions, including parts of North Africa and the Sahel, facilitating broader terrorist activities.

trgt: The souls of the righteous dead are in light and rest, with a foretaste of eternal happiness; but the souls of the wicked are in a state the reverse of this. Among the latter, such souls as have departed with faith but "without having had time to bring forth fruits worthy of repentance ... may be aided towards the attainment of a blessed resurrection [at the end of time] by prayers offered in their behalf, especially those offered in union with the oblation of the bloodless sacrifice of the Body and Blood of Christ, and by works of mercy done in faith for their memory."
trgt_first: The Eastern Orthodox Church holds that it is necessary to believe in this intermediate after-death state in which souls are perfected and brought to full divinization, a process of growth rather than of punishment, which some Orthodox have called purgatory. Eastern Orthodox theology does not generally describe the situation of the dead as involving suffering or fire, although it nevertheless describes it as a "direful condition".
mgt: The souls of the righteous dead are escorted by angels and experience a state of comfort, often referred to as the "Bosom of Abraham," which serves as a foretaste of the joy of paradise. In contrast, the souls of the wicked remain in darkness, awaiting judgment. Souls that depart with faith but without sufficient repentance may be aided by the prayers and liturgies of the Church, as well as acts of charity performed by the faithful. The ultimate goal for these souls is to attain rest and purification, with indulgenced prayers being particularly beneficial for their relief.

trgt: These defects become the failure sources or origin of damage induced in the composite. Due to laser polishing, the failure behavior of the composite changes because of combined elastoplastic behavior of the newly polished fiber and matrix at the workpiece surface. Furthermore, since melted surface material flows from peak to unfilled valleys, many defects are removed. This also causes re-bonding of the matrix-matrix as well as matrix-fiber essentially improving the tensile strength as well as dynamic mechanical properties by creating a much denser structure.
trgt_first: For this specific case, the workpiece is fabricated with Fused Deposition Modelling (FDM), an additive manufacturing method. Typically, all the additively manufactured components have defects throughout their matrix, viz. gas porosity, gap between deposited layers, inconsistent lamination of the deposited layers and low adhesion among layers. All of the aforementioned terms have related or unrelated reasons of formation which can be studied in depth, but are beyond scope of this summary.
mgt: During laser polishing, the melted surface material flows from the peaks into unfilled valleys, effectively removing surface defects and enhancing the bonding between the matrix and fibers. This process re-bonds the matrix-matrix and matrix-fiber interfaces, leading to improved tensile strength and dynamic mechanical properties. The combined behavior of the newly polished fiber and matrix at the workpiece surface results in a more uniform and dense structure, ultimately creating a composite with enhanced structural integrity and performance.

trgt: Danny Valentine (David Judge) had made a faulty repair to a boiler, causing a carbon monoxide leak that left Kris, John Paul McQueen (James Sutton), Katy Fox (Hannah Tointon), Summer (Summer Strallen), Zak Ramsey (Kent Riley), Carmel McQueen (Gemma Merna), Russ Owen (Stuart Manning), and other students unconscious. Justin Burton (Chris Fountain) later arrived to try and win Katy back and instead found everyone unconscious. After ringing Danny and finding that the boiler faulty, the pair carried everyone out saving them in the process. The storyline which had touched a very common issue in everyday life, helped save the life of regular Hollyoaks viewer Beth Cordingly, who was watching the episode when she was experiencing the same ordeal.
trgt_first: Another storyline the character was involved in a carbon monoxide poisoning plot.
mgt: In this storyline, Danny Valentine made a faulty repair to a boiler, which caused a dangerous carbon monoxide leak. The consequence of this botched repair was that several characters, including Katy Fox, became unconscious due to the poisoning. Justin Burton later arrived, hoping to win Katy back, but found her and others unconscious. Concerned for their safety, he contacted emergency services for help. After discovering the faulty boiler, Justin and Danny worked to address the situation. This storyline had a real-life impact, as Beth Cordingly credited watching the episode with alerting her to her own symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, ultimately saving her life.

section_title: == 1908–1928: Beginnings as an arm of the World Zionist Organization ==
trgt: Article 4 of the Mandate provided for "the recognition of an appropriate Jewish agency as a public body for the purpose of advising and co-operating with the Administration of Palestine in such economic, social and other matters as may affect the establishment of the Jewish National Home and the interests of the Jewish population of Palestine." The ZO leaders had contributed to the drafting of the Mandate. In November 1921, the Zionist Commission became the Palestine Zionist Executive and was designated as the Jewish agency for Palestine for the purpose of Article 4 of the Palestine Mandate.
trgt_first: On 25 April 1920, the Principal Allied Powers agreed at the San Remo conference to allocate the Ottoman territories to the victorious powers and assigned Palestine, Transjordan and Iraq as Mandates to Britain, with the Balfour Declaration being incorporated into the Palestine Mandate. The League of Nations formally approved these mandates in 1922.
mgt: Article 4 of the Mandate provided for the establishment of a Jewish agency to facilitate Jewish immigration and settlement in Palestine. The Zionist Commission was rebranded as the Palestine Zionist Executive in 1921, and in November of that year, it was designated as the Jewish Agency for the purposes of the Mandate. The Palestine Zionist Executive's role was to act as a representative body for the Jewish community in Palestine, aligning with the objectives outlined in Article 4, which aimed to promote the establishment of a Jewish national home.

trgt: With this development in tip geometry, it became economical to saw alloy steel billets. In 1969, Advanced Machine & Engineering Co. (AME) of Rockford, Illinois developed the first Billet Saw which used carbide tipped saw blades incorporating the "Braunschweig geometry". AME began to build these machines for the company Metalcut Inc., another Rockford based company. The machine was sold on the global market under the name Metalcut 12 and was exhibited at trade shows in Milan, Italy, and Chicago. Its cutting efficiency was eight times faster than band saws and four times faster than HSS circular cold saws and revolutionized the production sawing market.
trgt_first: In 1963, the American Company, Ingersoll Milling Machine Co. in Rockford, Illinois, developed the first carbide plate saw that was used to cut steel plates with carbide tipped circular saw blades. The positive cutting angle of the teeth minimized the life of the tool. Between 1963 and 1969, professor Pahlitzsch and engineers Arno Willemeit and Horst Doepcke at the University of Braunschweig, developed new carbide tip geometry with a negative cutting angle and a pair of teeth which split the chip into three parts.
mgt: This development made it economical to saw alloy steel billets. In 1969, Advanced Machine & Engineering Co. (AME) of Rockford, Illinois, developed the first Billet Saw, which utilized carbide tipped saw blades incorporating the "Braunschweig geometry." This geometry featured 18 degrees of negative cutting angles and chamfered edges to prevent breakage. AME began building these machines for Metalcut Inc., also based in Rockford. The machine was sold globally under the name Metalcut 12 and was exhibited at trade shows in Milan, Italy, and Chicago, showcasing its innovative design and capabilities in cutting alloy steel.

trgt: A review by Wyndham Wallace for the BBC said, "Much of Sonnamble's work is improvised, but there's an art to what they do: Curran’s homemade software seems able to reduce every note down to its even smaller constituent parts and then sieve out what suits their goal. The sound is therefore strangely granular, with the opening notes of Aphelion I spreading out and blurring at the edges until they distort and flutter into tiny sounds of their own. It's like moving one's face ever closer to a TV screen, with the picture slowly reduced from an overall pattern to a mass of pixels. What is experienced isn't identifiable in any standard sense, but is nonetheless fascinating."
trgt_first: Sonnamble's second album. Blindlight, was released in 2011 on Forwind. "Again the focus is on Marsh's lap steel guitar, whose drones, chords and twangs are coaxed into expansive ambient fuzziness or atomised into grains of noise by Curran's home-cooked software patches. But there's a spareness and a more pronounced spikiness to the music this time round; it's still immersive stuff, but more edgy...".
mgt: Wyndham Wallace wrote a review for the BBC about Sonnamble's work, noting that much of it is improvised and characterized by an intellectual approach where melody and rhythm are secondary. Curran's homemade software reduces each note to its smaller constituent parts, creating a strangely granular sound. The review describes the opening notes of "Aphelion I" as spreading out and blurring until they distort into tiny sounds. Wallace uses the analogy of moving closer to a TV screen, where the picture transforms from an overall pattern into a mass of pixels. This experience is characterized as fascinating yet not identifiable in any standard sense, emphasizing the abstract nature of Sonnamble's music.

section_title: == Peg Goldberg and the Kanakaria mosaics ==
trgt: These mosaics have fallen into destruction because of the damage that they experienced through the process of removal from the church, shipping around the world, and during the restoration work that Goldberg commissioned. It is unlikely that these mosaics will ever be reinstalled in their original home, even if there are changes in the political situation on Cyprus, because they would most likely not make it through the re-installation process in the state that they are currently in.
trgt_first: The mosaic pieces that were involved in the Kanakaria case have four different religious images. They depict Jesus as a young boy, the archangel Michael, Matthew and James; the final two are images of apostles from the 1st century. The mosaics were named after the Church in which they were placed originally around 530.
mgt: The destruction of the Kanakaria mosaics was primarily caused by the iconoclastic period in the 8th and 9th centuries, which led to the loss of many early Christian artworks. The mosaics were further damaged when Turkish art dealer Aydin Dikman looted them in the late 1970s. Restoration work has been commissioned by Cyprus' Byzantine Museum, but the likelihood of reinstallation in their original home remains uncertain, contingent on ongoing legal and diplomatic efforts. Concerns about their current state include fragmentation and potential loss of authenticity.

trgt: Many animals evolved including mammoths, giant ground sloths, dire wolves, saber-toothed cats, and most famously Homo sapiens. 100,000 years ago marked the end of one of the worst droughts in Africa, and led to the expansion of primitive humans. As the Pleistocene drew to a close, a major extinction wiped out much of the world's megafauna, including some of the hominid species, such as Neanderthals. All the continents were affected, but Africa to a lesser extent. It still retains many large animals, such as hippos.
trgt_first: The Pleistocene lasted from 2.58 million to 11,700 years ago. This epoch was marked by ice ages as a result of the cooling trend that started in the Mid-Eocene. There were at least four separate glaciation periods marked by the advance of ice caps as far south as 40° N in mountainous areas. Meanwhile, Africa experienced a trend of desiccation which resulted in the creation of the Sahara, Namib, and Kalahari deserts.
mgt: During the Quaternary, large mammals such as mammoths, mastodons, and ground sloths evolved, but many faced extinction as the Pleistocene drew to a close around 11,000 years ago. This extinction event primarily affected North and South America and Australia, while Africa experienced fewer losses due to its long history of cohabitation with large mammals. Notably, Africa retained species like elephants and rhinoceroses. Additionally, around 100,000 years ago, a significant drought in Africa ended, leading to a more favorable climate that supported diverse ecosystems.

mgt: In 1995, Yoko Ono supervised a remix of *Live Peace in Toronto 1969* for its compact disc issue, with assistance from Rob Stevens. The CD was released on 1 May 1995. The remixed version features additional backing vocals from Ono on "Dizzy Miss Lizzy," while "Money" has fewer backing vocals from her. trgt: Only the strongest electrophiles are able to do this, and these are usually dications or, more rarely, monocations, since high electrophilicity is accompanied by a substantial lack of electrons. In contrast, it is impossible for nucleophiles, which provide electrons for bond formation, to bind a noble gas strongly, because noble gases have negative electron affinities. Only weak interactions (ion- induced dipole and dispersion) are usually present, and do not result in a stable bond at room temperature.
trgt_first: Later, the term superelectrophilic was also frequently applied in gas phase studies to highly reactive dications that can bind noble gases at room temperature. Noble gases are generally considered to be particularly inert - in order to form a stable bond with a noble gas atom, a pair of electrons must be abstracted from it.
mgt: Strong binding of noble gases is typically achieved by highly reactive electrophiles, such as cationic dications or monocations, which possess high electrophilicity due to their positive charge. Nucleophiles, while capable of forming bonds, cannot bind noble gases strongly because noble gases have negative electron affinities and cannot accept electrons. The interactions between nucleophiles and noble gases are weak and do not result in stable bonds at room temperature, as the noble gases' closed electron shells resist chemical attack.

trgt: Claws are pointed at their ends and are composed of two layers: a thick, deep layer and a superficial, hardened layer which serves a protective function. The underlying bone is a virtual mold of the overlying horny structure and therefore has the same shape as the claw or nail. Compared to claws, nails are flat, less curved, and do not extend far beyond the tip of the digits. The ends of the nails usually consist only of the "superficial", hardened layer and are not pointed like claws.
trgt_first: In contrast to nails, claws are typically curved ventrally (downwards in animals) and compressed sideways. They serve a multitude of functions—including climbing, digging, and fighting—and have undergone numerous adaptive changes in different animal taxa.
mgt: The ends of claws are characterized by a hardened, superficial layer composed of multiple layers of keratin, which provides strength and durability. Beneath this layer lies the underlying bone, known as the ungual bone, which supports the overlying horny structure. In comparison to claws, nails are generally flatter and less curved. While claws exhibit significant curvature to enhance grip and functionality, nails typically have a more uniform shape. The ends of nails usually consist of a smooth, hard nail plate formed from tightly packed keratinized cells.

trgt: Returned to the United States were approximately 10,000,000 acres (4,000,000 ha; 40,000 km2) of territory near lakes Superior and Michigan and in Maine. American-held areas of Upper Canada (now Ontario) were returned to British control, but the Americans only returned Pensacola to Spanish Florida. All of Spanish West Florida west of the Perdido River, including the important port of Mobile, was occupied by the Americans in 1813, but the Treaty of Ghent did not force the Americans to leave this section of West Florida. The treaty made no changes to the prewar boundaries on the U.S.-Canada border.
trgt_first: The treaty released all prisoners and restored all captured lands and ships between the United States and Britain (Mobile and Spanish West Florida territory west of the Perdido River were not returned to Spain, who allied with Britain and the Red Stick Creeks in the War of 1812, by the United States).
mgt: The Treaty of Ghent did not specify the return of any territory to the United States, as the status of Spanish West Florida west of the Perdido River remained unresolved. However, the Americans retained control of approximately 23,000 acres of land, including the important port of Mobile. Areas held by Americans, such as parts of Upper Canada, were returned to British control. The treaty did not require Americans to vacate the section of West Florida west of the Perdido River, nor did it alter the prewar boundaries along the U.S.-Canada border.

The design included a double envelope; the internal layer black polyester, while the outer was transparent. He hired Cameron Balloons in Bristol to build solar balloon G-BAVU.
mgt: The transparent surface in the solar balloon's envelopes helped to reduce convection losses, allowing for better heat retention. The black envelope absorbed solar energy, providing the necessary buoyancy by heating the air inside. The twin envelopes were attached to a valve system that facilitated altitude control and deflation. The gas burner was used to maintain temperature when solar heating was insufficient. The solar balloon G-BAVU participated in hot air balloon festivals in England during the years 1981 to 1983, showcasing its innovative design and capabilities.

section_title: == US and USSR military and economic issues ==
trgt: This buildup was accelerated by the Reagan administration, which increased the military spending from 5.3 percent of GNP in 1981 to 6.5 percent in 1986, the largest peacetime defense buildup in United States history. The American-Soviet tensions present during 1983 was defined by some as the start of "Cold War II". Whilst in retrospective this phase of the Cold War was generally defined as a "war of words", the Soviet's "peace offensive" was largely rejected by the West.
trgt_first: By the early 1980s, the USSR had built up a military arsenal and army surpassing that of the United States. Soon after the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, president Carter began massively building up the United States military.
mgt: "However, it was President Reagan's administration that significantly accelerated the military buildup, with military spending rising from 5.2% of GNP in 1981 to 6.2% in 1986. This buildup marked a pivotal moment in U.S. history, intensifying American-Soviet tensions, particularly in 1983, which some defined as a period of heightened confrontation. During this time, the Soviet Union attempted a 'peace offensive' to ease tensions, but the West largely responded with skepticism, maintaining its military commitments and strategies."

trgt: For nearly 50 years, the houses concealed entrances to the third largest military facility in Yugoslavia (after the underground Željava Air Base near Bihać and the Lora naval facility in Split, Croatia). The houses consist of a control residence, a building containing secure communication links, and a facility for technical support personnel. Along a corridor located in the first house, three 1.2-meter-thick metal doors protect a tunnel leading to the heart of the shelter, which is 280 meters deep and 202 meters long.
trgt_first: Visible from the outside of the complex are three nondescript houses, not marked on any map, in an isolated natural setting located along the Neretva River.
mgt: "For over 30 years, these houses concealed entrances to one of the largest military facilities in Yugoslavia, surpassed only by the military bases in Pula and Belgrade. The houses feature reinforced components, including metal doors that are 20 centimeters thick, protecting the tunnel that leads to a vast underground network. Along a corridor in the first house, there are various operational rooms, while the shelter itself measures 30 meters in depth and 50 meters in length, designed for extensive military use."

trgt: Debutantes were formally introduced into society by presentation to the monarch at royal court during the Court Drawing Rooms and Queen Charlotte's Ball until the practice was abolished by Queen Elizabeth II in 1958. Queen Charlotte's Ball ceased to function in 1976, but has been relaunched since, by former debutante Jennie Hallam-Peel, without the monarch's involvement, and with more limited uptake; debutantes instead curtsy to "Queen Charlotte's Birthday Cake".
trgt_first: The social season played a role in the political life of the country: the members of the two Houses of Parliament were almost all participants in the season. But the Season also provided an opportunity for the children of marriageable age of the nobility and gentry to be launched into society.
mgt: Young women from noble and gentry families were formally introduced into society by presentation to the monarch at royal court during events such as the Queen Charlotte's Ball. This practice was abolished in 1958 by Queen Elizabeth II. The Queen Charlotte's Ball ceased to function in 1976 but was relaunched under the patronage of the Duke of Somerset, where debutantes now curtsy to a giant birthday cake.

trgt: Jencks makes the point that Post-Modernism (like Modernism) varies for each field of art, and that for architecture it is not just a reaction to Modernism but what he terms double coding: "Double Coding: the combination of Modern techniques with something else (usually traditional building) in order for architecture to communicate with the public and a concerned minority, usually other architects." In their book, "Revisiting Postmodernism", Terry Farrell and Adam Furman argue that postmodernism brought a more joyous and sensual experience to the culture, particularly in architecture.
trgt_first: The intellectual scholarship regarding postmodernism and architecture is closely linked with the writings of critic-turned-architect Charles Jencks, beginning with lectures in the early 1970s and his essay "The Rise of Post Modern Architecture" from 1975. His magnum opus, however, is the book The Language of Post-Modern Architecture, first published in 1977, and since running to seven editions.
mgt: Jencks argues that Post-Modernism varies across different fields of art, describing it in architecture as a blend of modern techniques with "quotations" from traditional styles, a concept he refers to as double coding. This technique embeds multiple layers of meaning within a building, appealing to both professionals and the general public. In their book *Revisiting Postmodernism*, authors Terry Farrell and Adam Nathaniel Furman contend that postmodernism introduced a more joyous and sensual experience to architecture, particularly noting its impact on urban design and cultural expression.

trgt: A post-concert brawl broke out between the Graham and Sly entourages; Bubba Banks and Eddie Chin, having heard that Larry had hired a hit man to kill Sly, assaulted Graham's associates. Graham and his wife climbed out of a hotel window to escape, and Pat Rizzo gave them a ride to safety. Unable to continue working with Sly, Graham immediately quit the Family Stone and went on to start Graham Central Station, a successful band in the same vein as Sly and the Family Stone. Graham was replaced in the interim by Bobby Womack, and then by nineteen-year-old Rusty Allen.
trgt_first: After the release of Riot, additional lineup changes took place. In early 1972, reacting to Jerry Martini's probing about his share of the band's earnings, Sly hired saxophonist Pat Rizzo as a potential replacement though both ended up remaining in the band. Later that year, the tension between Sly Stone and Larry Graham reached its peak.
mgt: A post-concert brawl erupted between the entourages of Graham and Sly, triggered by allegations from Sly's personal manager, Bubba Banks, and bodyguard, Eddie Chin, who claimed that Larry had hired a hit man to kill Sly. During the chaos, Graham and his wife escaped by crawling out of a hotel window, assisted by Pat Rizzo. Following this incident, Graham left the Family Stone and went on to form his own band, Graham Central Station. He was temporarily replaced in the Family Stone by Bobby Womack, and later by nineteen-year-old Rusty Allen.

mgt: Ewing compares 'Doctorin' the Tardis' to a companion piece that beckons the dancefloor for those who remember the 1970s, while notably excluding the boy gangs of yobs and nerds from the celebration. He places the track in a line of descent from novelty songs like 'Hoots Mon' and 'Mouldy Old Dough', which capture the essence of their time more truly than some serious songs. Ewing also notes that 'Doctorin' the Tardis' shares a quality with 'Theme From S'Express', blending nostalgia with infectious energy.

trgt: : 158 At the aft end of the Starship spacecraft are six Raptor engines, three of which are designed for operation in the lower atmosphere, and the other three Raptor Vacuum engines are optimized to operate in the vacuum of space. A set of reaction control thrusters mounted at the spacecraft's exterior control the spacecraft's attitude while in space.
trgt_first: Starship has a total propellant capacity of 1,200 t (2,600,000 lb), divided into main tanks and header tanks. The header tanks are better insulated due to their position and are reserved for use to flip and land the spacecraft following reentry. About 130 L (34 US gal) of hydraulic fluid is used for the spacecraft's operations.
mgt: At the aft end of the Starship spacecraft, there are six Raptor engines: three designed for sea-level operation and three Raptor Vacuum engines optimized for the vacuum of space. The reaction control thrusters, mounted on the spacecraft, manage its orientation and attitude control while in space, ensuring precise maneuverability during missions.

However, seemingly contradicting this, in May 2011, Fielding appeared in an episode of the UK version of the Celebrity Ghost Stories series for the bio channel, with the entire UK series of Celebrity Ghost Stories being produced by Fielding's Antix Productions company.
mgt: In September 2011, Fielding presented an episode of Ghosthunting with featuring the cast of The Only Way Is Essex. She visited a haunted house with Olly Murs in an episode of Olly: Life on Murs in April 2012. During her appearances on BBC Radio 2 and The Alan Titchmarsh Show in October 2012, she discussed the paranormal and her ghost-hunting career, stating she would return to Most Haunted in 2013. Fielding returned to host Most Haunted in 2014, with the new series produced for the Freeview channel Really, known for its focus on paranormal programming.

trgt: The Administrator has all the executive and legislative authority of a governor of an overseas territory. A Chief Officer is appointed, and is responsible to the Administrator for the day-to-day running of the civil government, with subordinate Area Officers responsible for the civil administration of the two areas. No elections are held in the territory, although British citizens are normally entitled to vote in United Kingdom elections (as British Forces or overseas electors).
trgt_first: The territory is administered by an Administrator, who is also the Commander of British Forces Cyprus, which as of September 2022 is Air vice-marshal Peter J. M. Squires. The Administrator is officially appointed by the British monarch on the advice of the Ministry of Defence.
mgt: The Administrator has the authority to make laws for the peace, order, and good government of the Sovereign Base Areas. The day-to-day civil government is managed by the Chief Officer, who reports to the Administrator. Subordinate officers oversee various aspects of civil administration. Elections are not held in Akrotiri and Dhekelia; however, British citizens residing there are entitled to vote in UK parliamentary and local elections. The two areas are Akrotiri and Dhekelia.

trgt: He won the league title with PSV for the second time in a row on 8 May 2016. On 18 December 2015, Hendrix extended his contract with PSV until 2020.

PSV started the last matchday of the season level on points with Ajax, but had a goal difference that was one less than Ajax's. On that day, PSV defeated PEC Zwolle 3–1, while Ajax won 4–1 against De Graafschap. Hendrix was sidelined for the last four games of the season due to injury.

trgt: Those who scored higher in ambivalence rated the black confederate more positively in the success condition but more negatively in the failure condition than the white confederate. David Bell and Victoria Esses (2002) conducted a study indicated that response amplification occurs only when one believes that the ambivalent response is problematic. When ambivalent white Canadian students were given essays that emphasized the positivity or negativity of ambivalence (considering both the good and bad in a situation or person), only those in the negative condition engaged in response amplification.
trgt_first: For example, whites' evaluations of blacks who are presented positively or negatively tend to be more extreme than evaluations of similar white individuals. Hass et al. (1991) had white students participate in an experiment in which each of them worked with either a white or black confederate to complete a task. The confederate, as instructed by the experimenter, caused the failure or the successful achievement of the task. After the task, the white students rated the confederate's performance.
mgt: In this study, white students rated the black confederate more positively in the success condition, while they rated him more negatively in the failure condition. In contrast, the evaluations of the white confederate did not vary significantly between success and failure conditions. David Bell and Victoria Esses conducted a study on response amplification in 2002, indicating that this phenomenon occurs when ambivalent individuals are presented with clear social norms. The participants were ambivalent white Canadian students, who received essays that either praised or criticized black individuals.

trgt_first: On the night of November 26, 1943, the Enterprise introduced the experiment in the co-operative control of Avengers and Hellcats for night fighting, when the three-plane team from the ship broke up a large group of land-based bombers attacking Task Group TG 50.2. O'Hare volunteered to lead this mission to conduct the first-ever Navy nighttime fighter attack from an aircraft carrier to intercept a large force of enemy torpedo bombers. When the call came to man the fighters, Butch O'Hare was eating. He grabbed up part of his supper in his fist and started running for the ready room.
mgt: He was dressed in loose marine coveralls. The night fighter unit, dubbed the "Black Panthers," consisted of O'Hare and Ensign Warren Andrew "Andy" Skon flying F6F Hellcats, while the Squadron Commander of VT-6, LCDR John C. Phillips, piloted a TBF1-C Avenger. The unit was catapulted between 1758 and 1801 hours. The crew of the TBF included LTJG Hazen B. Rand, a radar specialist, and Alvin Kernan, A.B., AOM1/c. Their mission objective was to intercept and engage the incoming mass of Japanese bombers targeting the task group.

trgt: Once near the lines, they would allow themselves to be captured by Allied forces. From detention camps, a pre-arranged signal from them would lead to their release and immediate debriefing of intelligence gathered during their mission. Approximately 1,000 Rabbits were dropped into enemy territory between September 1950 and June 1951. Amazingly, more than 70 percent returned to friendly territory, providing key intelligence into North Korean activities.
trgt_first: Special female agents were also dropped with orders to attach themselves to the highest Chinese or North Korean officer and travel with him as far as possible toward the front lines. Unarmed, even without radios, their survival was totally dependent on their individual ability to deceive enemy officers they were sent out to approach. These female agents proved remarkably effective.
mgt: Once near the lines, the individuals would gather intelligence before being captured by enemy forces. After capture, they would be taken to detention camps, where their release would depend on completing "rehabilitative training." Upon release, they would often face challenges reintegrating into society. Between September 1950 and June 1951, approximately 112,000 Rabbits were dropped, with around 70,000 returning to friendly territory, providing critical information on enemy movements and strategies.

trgt: In later years, he described the affair as "a violent, though pure love and passion". This statement, however, needs to be read in the context of hardening public attitudes toward homosexuality in England and the severe sanctions (including public hanging) against convicted or even suspected offenders. The liaison, on the other hand, may well have been "pure" out of respect for Edleston's innocence, in contrast to the (probably) more sexually overt relations experienced at Harrow School. The poem "The Cornelian" was written about the cornelian that Byron received from Edleston.
trgt_first: The following autumn, he entered Trinity College, Cambridge, where he met and formed a close friendship with the younger John Edleston. About his "protégé" he wrote, "He has been my almost constant associate since October, 1805, when I entered Trinity College. His voice first attracted my attention, his countenance fixed it, and his manners attached me to him for ever." Byron composed Thyrza, a series of elegies, in his memory.
mgt: Byron later described his relationship with Edleston as a "violent, though pure, love and passion," reflecting the complexity of their bond amid a society that harshly condemned homosexuality. During Byron's time, public attitudes were increasingly prejudiced, with severe sanctions for homosexual acts, including imprisonment and even pillorying. The liaison was considered 'pure' due to its emotional depth rather than physical expression. Edleston, a Cambridge chorister, gifted Byron a carnelian stone, which inspired the poem "The Cornelian." Byron's experiences at Harrow School also included intimate relationships with younger boys, laying the groundwork for his later romantic entanglements.

trgt: On July 31, 2022, Al-Qaeda leader Ayman al-Zawahiri was killed by an R9X missile. In 2013, Obama appointed John Brennan as the new CIA Director and announced a new policy that required CIA operatives to determine with a "near-certainty" that no civilians would be hurt in a drone strike. The number of drone strikes fell substantially after the announcement of the new policy.
trgt_first: Starting in 2011, in response to Obama's attempts to avoid civilian casualties, the Hellfire R9X "flying Ginsu" missile was developed. It is usually fired from drones. It does not have an explosive warhead that causes a large area of destruction but kills by using six rotating blades that cut the target into shreds.
mgt: On July 31, 2022, Al-Qaeda leader Ayman al-Zawahiri was killed by an R9X missile in a U.S. drone strike in Kabul, Afghanistan. In 2013, Barack Obama appointed John Brennan as Director of the CIA and announced a new drone strike policy requiring CIA operatives to ensure "near certainty" that no civilians would be harmed, leading to a reduction in the number of drone strikes.

trgt: Ford carried out observations with a range of single-lens microscopes, adding to our knowledge of van Leeuwenhoek's work. In Ford's opinion, Leeuwenhoek remained imperfectly understood, the popular view that his work was crude and undisciplined at odds with the evidence of conscientious and painstaking observation. He constructed rational and repeatable experimental procedures and was willing to oppose received opinion, such as spontaneous generation, and he changed his mind in the light of evidence.
trgt_first: In 1981, the British microscopist Brian J. Ford found that van Leeuwenhoek's original specimens had survived in the collections of the Royal Society of London. They were found to be of high quality, and all were well preserved.
mgt: Ford's research highlighted that Leeuwenhoek conducted observations with a range of single-lens microscopes, challenging the notion that he was merely an outsider in the scientific community. Contrary to the popular view that his work was largely unrecognized, Ford provided evidence of Leeuwenhoek's meticulous procedures and his opposition to the doctrine of spontaneous generation. In light of this evidence, Leeuwenhoek consistently produced observations that supported his belief that microbial organisms must have parents.

trgt: The farm was estimated to be able to produce £2m worth of cannabis per year using £250,000 worth of stolen electricity, with a crop of 4,000 plants every six weeks. The lighting equipment alone was estimated to have cost about £140,000. Three men admitted conspiracy to produce class B drugs and abstracting electricity. Charges of conspiracy to hold persons in slavery or servitude were initially made, but dropped due to lack of evidence. It took ten days to search and clear the site, which was said to be the biggest cannabis factory found in the southwest region. Custodial sentences were imposed on the three men in August 2017.
trgt_first: During the night of 22 February 2017, officers from Wiltshire Police raided the bunker following information received that it had been converted for use as a cannabis farm. There are approximately 20 rooms in the building, split over two floors, each 200 feet long and 70 feet wide. Almost every room had been converted for the wholesale production of cannabis plants, and there was a large amount of evidence of previous crops.
mgt: The estimated annual production value of cannabis at the farm was around £2 million, with approximately £650,000 worth of stolen electricity used annually to power the operation. The setup was capable of producing a crop every six weeks. The lighting equipment alone was valued at approximately £140,000. Three men—Martin Fillery, Plamen Nguyen, and Ross Winter—admitted to conspiracy to produce class B drugs and abstracting electricity, while initial charges of holding persons in slavery or servitude were dropped due to lack of evidence. It took about 10 days to search and clear the site, and custodial sentences were imposed on 11 August 2017.

mgt: Later in 2006, the iconic music show Top of the Pops was cancelled after 42 years on air, primarily due to declining ratings over the past five years as music and TV streaming changed viewing habits. Additionally, traditional live Saturday morning children's programmes on BBC and ITV ended after 40 years, facing similar rating declines in the preceding four years.

trgt: Salisbury nevertheless appointed Randolph as Chancellor of the Exchequer from 3 August 1886. Randolph proceeded to present budget proposals that went against the grain of Tory policy and faced opposition from the rest of the Cabinet. Outraged, Randolph sent Salisbury a letter of resignation on 22 December. Nevertheless, he arrogantly expected the Cabinet to back down so that he could continue on his own terms. Salisbury accepted his resignation and Randolph was out of frontline politics, never (unlike Winston) to return. He died young, aged 45, of a debilitating illness that may have been syphilis.
trgt_first: Randolph's political career was chequered and he could perhaps be described as someone with talent who completely wasted it, mostly by unacceptably immature behaviour of which the worst trait was rudeness. He made an enemy of Robert Cecil, 3rd Marquess of Salisbury (1830–1903), who first became Prime Minister in 1885. Salisbury probably summarised Randolph very aptly when he described him as the "antithesis of the Mahdi" – Muhammad Ahmad (1848–1885). Salisbury said the Mahdi "pretends to be half mad and is very sane in reality".
mgt: On 3 August 1886, Salisbury appointed Randolph as Chancellor of the Exchequer. His budget proposals, which aimed to impose protective tariffs, faced opposition from both the Liberal Party and some members of his own Conservative Party. After sending a letter of resignation to Salisbury on 20 December 1886, Randolph expected the Cabinet to reconsider his position. However, Salisbury accepted his resignation without dispute. Following this, Randolph did not return to frontline politics and died at the age of forty-five, with a brain tumor suggested as the likely cause of his death.

trgt: If molecules, atoms, or electrons, are emitted from material and their velocities are measured, the spectrum of their velocities often nearly obeys a theoretical law called the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution, which gives a well-founded measurement of temperatures for which the law holds. There have not yet been successful experiments of this same kind that directly use the Fermi–Dirac distribution for thermometry, but perhaps that will be achieved in the future.
trgt_first: In an ideal gas, and in other theoretically understood bodies, the Kelvin temperature is defined to be proportional to the average kinetic energy of non-interactively moving microscopic particles, which can be measured by suitable techniques. The proportionality constant is a simple multiple of the Boltzmann constant.
mgt: When molecules, atoms, or electrons are emitted from material, their velocities often nearly obey the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution, which provides a measurement of the distribution of kinetic energies. This distribution is well-founded under conditions of thermodynamic equilibrium. While successful experiments have utilized the Fermi–Dirac distribution for thermometry, future advancements may enable its broader application in measuring temperatures in systems with fermionic particles.
